    <text>
        <body>
      
		<pb n="1"/>
			<p rend="align(right)"><placeName>In dem Meeserschen Hause<lb/> &#252;ber der Br&#252;cke<lb/> am Neckar <hi rend="underline">Heidelberg</hi></placeName></p>
			<p rend="align(right)"><date>March 9<hi rend="sup">th</hi> 1854</date></p>
			<p>Dear friend</p>
          <p rend="indent(2)">I am taking the opportunity<lb/> of writing a little to you by a Gentleman<lb/> about to leave <placeName>Heidelberg</placeName> for <placeName>New York</placeName>. I<lb/> have not your correct address here&#59; I<lb/> therefore must trust to his kindness in<lb/> sending it safely to you at <placeName>Philadelphia</placeName>.<lb/> When I last heard from my dear family<lb/> one of my sisters wrote to say that the &#8220;<hi rend="underline">Occident</hi>&#8221;<lb/> had been sent to me in <placeName>Baker<add>&#63;</add></placeName> in which they read<lb/> a <hi rend="underline">beautiful</hi> notice of my Poems from<lb/> your gifted mind&#44; with some pieces<lb/> transcribed. I assure you I appreciate<lb/> <hi rend="underline">much</hi> your kindness also for the<lb/> advertisement therein&#8212;my sisters have<lb/> requested two more copies to be sent<lb/> for them &#38; I am to receive <hi rend="underline">my</hi><lb/> number in <date>May</date>&#44; when <persName>Mr Simon&#39;s</persName><lb/> family are going to visit us&#44; en route</p>
		<pb n="2"/>
			<p>for <placeName>Switzerland</placeName>.</p>
			<p>I presume from this circumstance<lb/> that the books arrived safely at their<lb/> destination&#8212;&#38; that you have long<lb/> since obtained your <hi rend="underline">own</hi> rightful<lb/> copy. I hope also that my long letter<lb/> reached you from the &#8220;<add>&#63;</add>&#8221; where<lb/> we then resided. I wrote your address<lb/> quite from guess&#44; for I left my Occidents<lb/> with all my principal books to be<lb/> taken charge of.</p>
			<p>My dear friend <persName>Miss Brettell<add>&#63;</add></persName> has taken<lb/> with me these charming rooms facing<lb/> the Castle &#38; <placeName>Neckar</placeName> where we have<lb/> not only a most romantic picture<lb/> ever before our eyes&#44; but also every comfort<lb/> &#38; convenience in this beautiful House.<lb/> My <hi rend="underline">good</hi> Papa at length yielded to my<lb/> longing wish for a more <hi rend="underline">country</hi> life &#38;<lb/> now permits me to follow my inclination<del>s</del><lb/> which was never in favor of a residence<lb/> in our gay &#38; busy city of <placeName>London</placeName>&#33;</p>
			<p>It is&#44; as you may imagine&#44; an infinite<lb/> blessing to me thus to enjoy&#44; in more<lb/> retirement&#44; the glorious beauties of nature&#44;<lb/> &#38; my own favorite studies of Literature &#38;<lb/> music. I do not know yet how long we<lb/> may remain in <placeName>Heidelberg</placeName>. I think we<lb/> shall spend <date>June</date> &#38; <date>July</date> in <placeName>Switzerland</placeName><lb/> &#40;my 3d visit&#41; &#38; then most likely go to<lb/> <placeName>England</placeName> for a few months as we shall<lb/> both be <sic>anscious</sic> to see our friends there.</p>
			<p>We have had a <hi rend="underline">very</hi> severe winter&#44; but<lb/> to <hi rend="underline">me</hi> the charm has been so great<lb/> that I could not regret it. To see the<lb/> scenery here all enveloped in its <hi rend="underline">snowy</hi><lb/> mantle&#8212;has been a continual source<lb/> of enjoyment to me &#38; the tinkling<lb/> bells of the horses as they bore the gay<lb/> sledges along&#44; did not a little enhance the<lb/> beauty of the picture&#33;</p>
			<p>I suppose you hear as much of<lb/> the War as we do. Some people<lb/> are of opinion that it is the first</p>
		<pb n="3"/>
			<p>step towards the restoration of our<lb/> Nation&#8212;according to the Prophecies.<lb/> What is your opinion&#63; And how<lb/> goes on your interesting work&#44; the Bible&#63;</p> 
			<p>Have you heard of a <hi rend="underline">small</hi> book<lb/> published in <date>1853</date> at Chapman&#39;s in the<lb/> <placeName>Strand&#44; London</placeName> &#40;price 36 s. d.&#41; &#8220;<hi rend="underline">A few words to</hi><lb/> <hi rend="underline">the Jews</hi>&#8221;&#63; It is splendidly written&#44;<lb/> &#38; most touchingly beautiful&#8212;<lb/> We&#44; as Israelites&#44; cannot be too grateful<lb/> to God for raising amongst us such<lb/> an Author&#8212;so deeply imbued with the true<lb/> spirit of Judaism. I hope it will soon<lb/> be well known both in <placeName>England</placeName> &#38; <placeName>America</placeName>.<lb/> We do not know the name of the Author<lb/> not his place of abode&#8212;he merely adds<lb/> in the title page &#8220;by one of themselves.&#8221;<lb/> Surely he will one day be known&#33;<lb/> at present all is in mystery respecting the<lb/> books. My paper tells me to say farewell<lb/> for the present&#44; &#38; trusting you are in<lb/> good health&#44; I remain dear friend</p>
          <p rend="indent(1)">Your&#39;s sincerely&#44; <persName role="author">Rosa <add>&#63;</add> Salsman</persName></p>
          
